It should be noted that this arming of Turnus is not for the actual eombat (for that only takes place next day, cf. 113), but merely to assure himself that his armour is duly prepared and trustworthy. The real purpose of the two paragraphs (Sl-106 and 107-112) is to bring out in strong con- trast the ungoverned fury of Turnus and the calm confidence of Aeneas.
